{
  "texts": [
    "This accounts for the constant factor differences in h(N) for µ ̸ = 0.",
    "The solution to the above problem is trivial in the infinite limit: set all z i = 1, when µ < 0, and set half of the z i to 1 when µ > 0.However, to compensate for the maximum growing Θ( √ N) faster (than standard SK) when µ(N) is not always zero, we could consider defining the biased SK model to haveµ(N) = O(N -1/2).",
    "Then letting µ = lim N →∞ µ(N) √ N we get, from Equation (79), 0 ≤ lim N →∞ E J [max z G(z)] N 3/2 - µ 2(1 + sign(µ)) ≤ σ √ 2 log 1/2 (4).",
    "(84)Thus the growth of the maximum is again O(N 3/2), like in the original SK.",
    "Recall that the original SK satisfies0 ≤ lim N →∞ E J [max z G(z)] N 3/2 ≤ σ √ 2 log 1/2 (4),(85)with the limiting value being the Parisi value."
  ]
}